WEBVTT

00:00.948 --> 00:04.342
I'm not going to annihilate
4.3 million Pakistanis

00:04.485 --> 00:07.292
without hearing from someone
whose authority I recognize.

00:07.376 --> 00:08.815
Our own people
tried to sink us?

00:08.949 --> 00:09.863
We have commandeered

00:10.031 --> 00:11.086
the NATO early warning station

00:11.192 --> 00:12.547
on the island of Sainte Marina.

00:12.667 --> 00:14.813
I am declaring
a 200-mile no-man's-land

00:14.919 --> 00:15.998
around this island.

00:16.123 --> 00:19.167
Test us, and we will all burn.

00:19.474 --> 00:21.174
You've been warned.

00:21.682 --> 00:23.017
The only two people
who know you're still alive

00:23.142 --> 00:23.885
are the two you're looking at.

00:23.990 --> 00:24.746
And that's lucky for you.

00:24.848 --> 00:27.002
I know a couple of Navy SEALs
that would love to come say hi.

00:27.114 --> 00:28.082
Where's the fifth black op?

00:28.190 --> 00:28.794
There were four.

00:28.896 --> 00:30.445
No, you buried four,
but there were five.

00:30.547 --> 00:31.942
My lawyer Paul Wells,

00:32.057 --> 00:34.423
he's an old friend of Sam's,
and he's been amazing.

00:34.525 --> 00:36.652
But he's a government agent
sent to spy on me

00:36.773 --> 00:38.002
and turn me against Sam.

00:38.088 --> 00:39.611
Plug it into
the USB port of the car.

00:39.713 --> 00:41.696
Every time the driver makes
a call through the hands-free,

00:41.842 --> 00:43.788
you get the call on this.

00:43.885 --> 00:45.507
Why steal the firing
key? Why not reach out?

00:45.584 --> 00:46.477
Why not form an alliance?

00:46.575 --> 00:47.832
The word among sub captains
for a while

00:47.934 --> 00:49.564
has been that the CIA
has a sleeper agent

00:49.684 --> 00:50.758
on every nuclear sub,

00:50.848 --> 00:52.848
just in case some crazy captain
gets the wrong idea.

00:52.954 --> 00:54.729
Your sleeper will be
communicating with Langley

00:54.841 --> 00:56.292
by a secure radio channel,

00:56.442 --> 00:58.727
which means there's a comm site
somewhere on this island.

00:58.814 --> 00:59.660
We look for the comm site.

00:59.773 --> 01:01.708
We find the traitor,
we find the key.

01:03.014 --> 01:04.438
All right.
Listen up, people.

01:04.590 --> 01:05.233
In five days,

01:05.404 --> 01:06.698
a ship will be allowed
through the blockade

01:06.809 --> 01:08.760
to transport those of you
who have elected to leave

01:08.904 --> 01:10.063
back to the States.

01:10.255 --> 01:12.914
This ship will also be
delivering food and provisions

01:13.156 --> 01:14.025
a whole lot better

01:14.132 --> 01:15.788
than the beans and rice
we've had lately.

01:15.974 --> 01:17.056
Yeah!

01:17.163 --> 01:19.537
We've also negotiated
a 24-hour visit

01:19.736 --> 01:21.646
with your spouses
and family members.

01:23.210 --> 01:24.218
Yeah!

01:24.765 --> 01:26.094
I'll have more details shortly,

01:26.205 --> 01:27.961
but many of you are gonna
see your family again.

01:32.034 --> 01:33.445
Hey, Anders, I know
it's not going home,

01:33.567 --> 01:35.553
but at least you're gonna
get to see your wife.

01:36.949 --> 01:38.439
She's not gonna be
on that ship.

01:46.032 --> 01:47.107
So what do you think?

01:47.829 --> 01:50.154
I don't know. It seems
too good to be true, no?

01:50.337 --> 01:51.854
The government is spinning
every top on the table

01:51.966 --> 01:53.428
to buy some good PR.

01:53.725 --> 01:55.875
You know they're not gonna
let Christine come.

01:56.058 --> 01:57.809
No one for Grace or me either.

01:59.119 --> 02:00.262
Right. Well, they want
to drive a wedge

02:00.382 --> 02:02.095
between the officers
and enlisted, yeah?

02:02.196 --> 02:02.780
Yeah, sure.

02:02.886 --> 02:04.312
They cast us as the cause
of all their troubles,

02:04.415 --> 02:05.773
remind them what they're
missing at home.

02:05.877 --> 02:07.296
It's a smart move,
and they've got me in a bind.

02:07.399 --> 02:08.538
You say "yes," they look good.

02:08.661 --> 02:10.588
You say "no," you keep looking
like the crazy bastard

02:10.723 --> 02:12.031
who doesn't give a damn
about his crew.

02:12.142 --> 02:13.047
That's it.

02:13.164 --> 02:14.284
Hey, sir.

02:14.399 --> 02:15.933
We're still down a launch key.

02:16.078 --> 02:18.302
This thing goes sideways,
we're defenseless.

02:18.425 --> 02:20.295
Everyone who leaves this place
gets searched.

02:20.404 --> 02:21.724
We may not have
one of our keys,

02:21.826 --> 02:23.422
but I'm not gonna let someone
prove that to our enemies.

02:23.608 --> 02:24.250
Okay.

02:24.434 --> 02:26.439
How's it going with our friend
from the, uh, CIA?

02:26.534 --> 02:28.224
I'm the only face he's seen
for six days.

02:28.429 --> 02:29.900
And he likes to talk, so--

02:29.995 --> 02:32.111
Okay. Keep him talking.
See what you can find out.

02:40.103 --> 02:41.980
A hundred years ago,
we were self-sufficient.

02:42.092 --> 02:43.241
Our culture was pure.

02:43.354 --> 02:44.785
That's what seduced me
back to this island.

02:44.882 --> 02:46.020
There are enough provisions
on the ship

02:46.131 --> 02:47.314
to feed us all
for at least a month.

02:47.425 --> 02:48.724
A month? Tani.

02:48.839 --> 02:50.943
How much is a pound of flour
going for these days?

02:51.050 --> 02:53.554
Sorry, father. I'm not
letting you drag me into this.

02:53.663 --> 02:55.695
Do you need help
dealing with Serrat?

02:55.806 --> 02:57.281
Serrat leaves my people alone.

02:57.374 --> 02:58.684
The problem begins and ends

02:58.797 --> 03:00.293
with that blockade of ships
out there.

03:00.410 --> 03:01.783
I will do everything
in my power

03:02.004 --> 03:03.421
to fix this.

03:05.088 --> 03:06.924
You know you can't fix
what you are.

03:07.033 --> 03:08.623
And maybe your heart's
in the right place,

03:08.725 --> 03:10.198
but finally, you're no better
than the French

03:10.320 --> 03:11.804
when they took this island
and raided it

03:11.924 --> 03:13.343
for anything of value.

03:13.445 --> 03:14.677
That's true.

03:14.948 --> 03:16.671
We are who we are.

03:16.783 --> 03:18.832
And now we're here,
and that might not change.

03:18.929 --> 03:20.235
So...

03:20.915 --> 03:22.488
you might have to.

03:28.378 --> 03:30.081
This is hard for them, too.

03:30.193 --> 03:32.471
How long do you think you can
keep one foot in the water

03:32.735 --> 03:34.156
and the other on the shore?

03:36.175 --> 03:36.913
<i>Grasshopper.</i>

03:37.029 --> 03:39.507
- It's shortwave. It's very difficult
to locate. <i>- Earthquake.</i>

03:39.620 --> 03:40.969
- So I can tell you it's on the island...
<i>- One.</i>

03:41.066 --> 03:42.847
- but I can't tell you where.
- Okay.

03:42.981 --> 03:44.725
<i>Three. Airport.</i>

03:44.904 --> 03:46.806
<i>- Two.</i>
- Anything else I can do for you?

03:46.914 --> 03:47.864
<i>- Hopscotch.</i>
- No. Just tell me

03:47.965 --> 03:49.552
- when you find out more
about the signals. <i>- Six.</i>

03:49.676 --> 03:50.570
<i>Four.</i>

03:50.721 --> 03:51.998
<i>- Bookworm.</i>
- Okay.

03:52.113 --> 03:54.696
<i>Five. Six.</i>

